          <td bgcolor="" valign="top"><!-- #BeginEditable "Body" --> 
            <table width=100% border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0>
<tr><td width=1><img src="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_01.gif" width=6 height=6></td><td width=100% background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_02.gif"></td>
<td width=1><img src="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_03.gif" width=6 height=6></td></tr>
<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_04.gif"><img src="/lotr/gfx/mom/clear.gif" height=35 width=1></td>
<td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_05.gif" class="headerbg"><font class="h1font"><font color="#FFFFFF"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/starwarsccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magination/articles/articles.php'>Magi-Nation Duel</option><option value='/swtcg/articles/articles.php'>Star Wars TCG</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></B></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_06.gif"></td></tr>
	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> Deck Burning<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.71)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=11682'>Paul "Hetfool" Twomey</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=11682&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> August 6, 2002</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> A balance must be struck in every deck that ensures a player is able to utilize his or her entire deck during any given game unless your strategy is such that this is not an option. However speaking in general, most people use space in their decks effectively and would like the opportunity to play as much as they can.<br />
<br />
If a player could play his whole hand each turn you would require up wards of 160 cards (based on both opponents moving one site at a time) and clearly this is not an option considering any hand will consist of both Shadow and Free-Peoples cards. Even so, if a player could play four cards each turn (8 for both the Shadow and Free-Peoples turn and based again on both opponents moving one site at a time) then you would need upwards of 80 cards to make it to site 9 with enough in the draw deck to last the game. However any experienced player will tell you that an eighty-card deck is mighty hard to burn through in a game especially considering double, even triple moves. The question then is how to judge what size your deck should be. <br />
<br />
It is not as simple as saying more than 60, but less than 80 is the best range for a deck, because your deck may be stacked in such a way that 80 cards will be way too much, or 60 will result in way too little. For example, if you are using Moria Swarm you will tend to churn out your shadow very fast at more than 4 cards per shadow phase in most cases and you will also be able to recycle cards rapidly too. This means a Moria Swarm deck can have a few extra bits and pieces as long as they too are in line with the low costs of Swarm decks. However if you were to play a traditional Nazgul deck, you may be in trouble with too many cards considering the combinations required and high cost of the Nazgul culture in general. All of this most of you already know, but the challenge here is how do you judge how fast your decks are, and what does that mean for your deck size.<br />
<br />
There are a number of approaches you can take to ensure you have an efficient deck and the most basic is called &#8220;dead card tally&#8221;. First tally up the number of cards in your deck and then list them on a piece of paper. For every card that requires a condition to be met, like spotting or exerting, place a 1 next to it. For every shadow card that costs more than 2 that does not have already have a 1, add another 1. If you have a discarding card then place a &#8211;1 next to that card, unless of course that card has a condition like spot, in that case add nothing. Finally go through the list and edit accordingly based on your playing experience, add 1 for cards you know normally take a while to play or mark a card as zero if you think you will be able to play it quickly. You can also do half points, for example Isengard Axe does require a Isengard Minion, but its cost is zero, this can be considered a half point. Finally add up your total and generate a percentage with the total number of cards in your deck. That percentage is called your &#8220;dead card percentage&#8221;. <br />
<br />
In an ideal game your looking for a flat 50% dead card percentage to ensure you can most likely produce 4 cards every turn. In a run deck it will need to be lower however and other strategies may affect what is a suitable percentage. This now gives you an idea of how fast your deck will be used, and will let you know if you can add more cards or you need to get rid of some. Obviously the rating process for each card does require some experience which makes this process a little subjective, but play testing will reveal how accurate this measure is and generally if you rate the cards correctly the percentage will be very close.<br />
<br />
Another use for this rating is in decision making during the game. Should you discard a useful card to pick up an extra? Should you use the discard or draw card ability now? You can try and keep a tally of how many cards you have played each turn and use that as a guide to see at what points during the game you need to recycle, or renew your hand. It is not difficult to judge as in all decks, turning over cards is just as important as playing them. This rating can also identify what opposing strategies will cause you pain, for instance a deck with a percentage above 55% that does not have a low costing shadow side will inevitably generate larger amounts of dead cards against a twilight denial deck. If your percentage is below 45% you can be in grave danger against any form of discard deck. However the same can be said for perfect 50% decks, if your up against a run deck you may find you will not get through most of your deck and your opponent has effectively neutralised a number of cards before you even get a chance to use them, because you will never get them. It is not the end of the world, but it is a fact you should be aware of and consider both in deck design and during the game.<br />
<br />
On a more advanced level it should be noted that as each site progresses you have a better chance to produce each card and meet the conditions on each card. Given this you can rate you deck against groups of sites like 1-3 or 7-9 and so on. This will give you a more accurate idea of what is possible later on in the game when your chances to play higher costing minions or site related cards increase. It will also let you know what kind of deck your playing, early or late or balanced. However if you undertake this effort you need to place a -1 on cards that will most definitely be used at a later site, or a 1 for a card that you would discard at that later site. For example, if you had a Horn of Boromir it would be a 1 early on unless Boromir was a starting companion. In the last few sites you can judge that Boromir would be out so this card is now 0. However if Boromir is a companion you will sacrifice then Horn becomes a 1. This method will help balance an early Fellowship with a late Shadow or another combination that you wish to create.<br />
<br />
It is not all an exact science, but if judged correctly it will let you know what your deck is really doing instead of having to rely on your judgement from game to game. It is also a useful tool to employ to make you aware of when you are in trouble during a game. <br />
